 existing approaches to production. The story of Genentech is an example of=
 this. The first therapeutic produced using genetic engineering&#8212;insul=
in&#8212;already existed as a medicine. Before the use of genetic engineeri=
ng, insulin was isolated and extracted from animals. Genentech&#8217;s majo=
r breakthrough was to replace highly wasteful and inefficient production me=
thods.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>The industrialization of recombinant DNA=
 made it possible to harness cells as miniature factories for the productio=
n of drugs</strong><span>. Genentech scaled this powerful process in a cent=
ralized structure like a pharmaceutical company, and now operates as a subs=
idiary of Roche.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Early examples of consumer products pr=
oduced using biotech have followed similar storylines. Pat Brown, who was a=
